04040nam a22006495i 9781442674448DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182000onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426744487 a10.3138/97814426744482doi  a(DE-B1597)497116  a(OCoLC)1078910344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a302.2/0300aEncyclopedic Dictionary of Semiotics, Media, and Communication /ced. by Marcel Danesi. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Studies in Semiotics and Communication00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tDictionary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSemiotics, Media Studies and Communication Studies are three closely interlinked fields. Briefly stated, Semiotics, the science of signs, looks at how humans search for and construct meaning; Communication Studies is concerned with how meaning is conveyed; and Media Studies considers the ways in which messages are transmitted and received. This dictionary is designed to help students and general readers unlock the significance of the terminology and jargon commonly used in these fields.Being interdisciplinary in nature, Semiotics, Media, and Communication Studies are cluttered with notions derived from other disciplines. Hence, this dictionary also encompasses basic concepts from the fields of anthropology, archaeology, psychology, psychoanalysis, linguistics, philosophy, artificial intelligence, computer science, and biology. Collected here are the terms, concepts, personages, schools of thought, and historical movements that appear frequently in the relevant literature.The basis of each entry is a simple definition, which often includes the term's origin. Illustrations are provided where necessary, along with historical sketches of movements or schools of thought. The commentary on personages consists of brief statements about their contribution and relevance. Thus, the dictionary not only defines what a term means, but often goes into its history, applications, and broad implications. Terms are cross-referenced and their etymology is given where possible. This is a compact, practical research manual that will relieve much tension for students in semiotics and related fields. Because of its interdisciplinary approach, it will also provide a range of scholars with a handy reference to disciplines distinct from but related to their own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunicationvDictionaries. 0aMass mediavDictionaries. 0aSemioticsvDictionaries. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aDanesi, Marcel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267444840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442674448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442674448.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK